ğŸ“– **Description:**
    The `getopt` command is used to parse command line options and arguments.  It helps scripts and programs process command-line input in a standardized and correct way.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ğŸ”¹ `getopt -o <shortopts> -- <command line>`  --> ğŸ« `-o` is used to define short (single character) options. For example, `-o ab:c::` means that `-a`, `-b` (which requires an argument), and `-c` (which takes an optional argument) are valid options.
    ğŸ”¹ `getopt -l <longopts> -- <command line>`  --> ğŸ·ï¸ `-l` is used to define long (multi-character) options. For example, `--long options,other-option:,another-option::`.
    ğŸ”¹ `getopt -n <name>` --> ğŸ“› `-n` is used to set the program name. This name is used in error messages.
    ğŸ”¹ `--` --> â›” Indicates the end of options; anything after `--` is treated as a non-option argument.

ğŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ getopt -o ab:c:: -- 'script.sh' -a -b 'value' -c 'another value' argument1 argument2

    ğŸ”¹ Parses options `-a`, `-b` (with argument), and `-c` (with optional argument) from the command line.

    $ getopt -l 'long-option,other-option:,another-option::' -- 'script.sh' --long-option --other-option 'value' --another-option argument1 argument2

    ğŸ”¹ Parses long options such as `--long-option`, `--other-option` (with argument), and `--another-option` (with optional argument).

âœ… **Simple Example:**

